# React & TypeScript Standards

## Linting & Formatting

This project uses ESLint and Prettier for code style:
- **Prettier config:** `.prettierrc` (root)
- **ESLint config:** `.eslintrc.json` (root, extends `@powerhome/eslint-config-nitro`)
- Components may have their own `.eslintrc.json` to override rules

**After making changes, ALWAYS run both Prettier and lint from the component directory:**
```bash
# Step 1: Auto-format with Prettier (fixes most style issues)
npx prettier --write app/javascript/YourAppName/

# Step 2: Verify everything passes (this is what CI runs)
yarn lint
```

CI runs `yarn lint` which executes **both** `eslint` AND `prettier -c`. Code that passes ESLint but fails Prettier will still fail CI. Always run both.

## Prettier Formatting Rules (REQUIRED)

The `.prettierrc` at the repo root enforces these rules. Agents should be aware of them when writing code to minimize Prettier diffs:

| Rule | Setting | What it means |
|---|---|---|
| `arrowParens` | `"avoid"` | Single-param arrows: `item =>` NOT `(item) =>` |
| `semi` | `false` | No semicolons at end of statements |
| `trailingComma` | `"es5"` | Trailing commas in arrays/objects/params |
| `singleQuote` | `false` | Use double quotes `"text"` not single `'text'` |
| `tabWidth` | `2` | 2-space indentation |
| `bracketSameLine` | `false` | Closing `>` on its own line for multi-line JSX |

```typescript
// CORRECT — matches Prettier config
const handleClick = event => {
  setState(prev => ({ ...prev, clicked: true }))
}

items.map(item => <Card key={item.id} padding="md" />)

// WRONG — Prettier will reformat these
const handleClick = (event) => {   // parens on single param
  setState((prev) => ({ ...prev, clicked: true }));  // parens + semicolons
}

items.map((item) => <Card key={item.id} padding="md" />)  // parens
```

**Line length:** Prettier wraps at 80 characters by default. Short JSX elements stay on one line; long ones get expanded to multi-line. Don't fight Prettier on line wrapping — just run `npx prettier --write` and let it decide.

## JSX Prop Ordering (REQUIRED)

This project enforces `react/jsx-sort-props` — **all JSX props must be in alphabetical order**. CI will fail with errors if props are not sorted.

```typescript
// CORRECT — props sorted alphabetically
<Flex align="center" gap="md" orientation="row" width="100%">
<Title bold color="default" size={4}>
<Button onClick={handleClick} size="md" text="Submit" variant="primary" />

// WRONG — props not sorted (will fail CI lint)
<Flex orientation="row" gap="md" align="center" width="100%">
<Title size={4} bold color="default">
```

**Rule:** Always write props in A-Z order. This applies to every JSX element — Playbook components, HTML elements, and custom components alike.

## One Component Per File (REQUIRED)

ESLint enforces `react/no-multi-comp` — **each `.tsx` file must export only one React component**. Helper components must be extracted into their own files.

```typescript
// WRONG — two components in one file (will trigger no-multi-comp)
const LabelValue = ({ label, value }: LabelValueProps) => (...)
const ProjectSummary = ({ data }: ProjectSummaryProps) => (...)
export default ProjectSummary

// CORRECT — extract LabelValue into LabelValue.tsx
// LabelValue.tsx
export const LabelValue = ({ label, value }: LabelValueProps) => (...)

// ProjectSummary.tsx
import { LabelValue } from "./LabelValue"
export const ProjectSummary = ({ data }: ProjectSummaryProps) => (...)
```

## No Console Statements

ESLint enforces `no-console` — **never use `console.log`, `console.warn`, or `console.error`**. Use proper error handling or remove debug logging before committing.

## No Empty Functions

ESLint enforces `@typescript-eslint/no-empty-function` — **empty function bodies are errors**. For placeholder callbacks, add an eslint-disable comment:

```typescript
// CORRECT — explicit disable for intentional no-op
// eslint-disable-next-line @typescript-eslint/no-empty-function
const noop = () => {}

// WRONG — empty function without disable
const noop = () => {}
```

## React Component Patterns

```typescript
// GOOD - Functional component with proper typing
type MyComponentProps = {
  count: number
  onAction?: () => void
  title: string
}

const MyComponent = ({ count, onAction, title }: MyComponentProps) => {
  return <div>{title}: {count}</div>
}

export default MyComponent
```

- Use **functional components** and type props directly in the function signature
- Define props as TypeScript types (not interfaces for simple cases)
- Use **named exports** for components

## Playbook UI Imports

Always import UI components from `playbook-ui`:
```typescript
import { Button, Card, Flex, FlexItem, Title, Body } from "playbook-ui"
```

Do NOT create custom UI primitives when Playbook has equivalents.

## Path Aliases

Use these configured aliases:
- `@powerhome/graphql/*` - GraphQL utilities
- `@powerhome/hooks/*` - Shared React hooks
- `@powerhome/kits/*` - Shared components

## Example Component

```typescript
import React, { useState } from "react"
import { Flex, FlexItem, Button } from "playbook-ui"

type CounterProps = {
  initialValue: number
}

const Counter = ({ initialValue }: CounterProps) => {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(initialValue)

  return (
    <Flex align="center" gap="md">
      <FlexItem>Count: {count}</FlexItem>
      <FlexItem>
        <Button onClick={() => setCount(c => c + 1)} text="Increment" />
      </FlexItem>
    </Flex>
  )
}

export default Counter
```
